+  /// which their registration takes place and their relation with the
+  /// DLL is lost. A situation can easily arise where the dynamic
+  /// service object is finalized and its DLL - unmapped, but some of
+  /// the DLL's static services may still be around. Their
+  /// finalization would not be possible, if the DLL containg that
+  /// code is gone. To prevent cases like this, we keep a handler for
+  /// the last DLL dlopen()-ed. On the current thread, there will be
+  /// just one and its handle will be kept here to be used by every
+  /// static service that registers itself. In the space between
+  /// dlopen()-ing a DLL and retrieving the symbol to call init() on,
+  /// any static service that registers will be associated with the
+  /// "current" DLL. During finalization, this will keep the reference
+  /// count positive, until the last static or dynamic service object
+  /// in a DLL is finalized, which will finally unload the DLL.
